Wow 10 years ago today I graduated from cosmetology school and 7 years ago today I opened the doors of my 1st salon suite. Damn man. 

10 years seem like such a long time ago, but I’m realizing it’s just a speck on the journey. I was 24 years old. I didn’t realize how much of a child I still was until looking at this. 
One hell of a decade!!
So much life has happened between then and now but one thing for sure I’m glad I took the chance and started! I dropped out of Kennesaw state the year prior and chose me. This was the second time I had done that and still top 2 best decisions of my life. 
I had this gut feeling way back then that being in corporate America wasn’t for a eccentric kid like me. I banked on myself. Still is. Always will.

Am I tripping?? 

Last year I suffered from depression and anxiety and I found the root to be that I was out of alignment with who I said I wanted to be. I was moving in a new direction but operating in old ways. It was internal conflict. Literally ME VS ME. 

Maybe so many of us are trying to escape because we can’t handle the mirror.

I remember this used to be me. 
Constantly overwhelmed, worried about content, feeling like I wasn’t showing up enough. 

Like why must I be a videographer, editor, and social media marketer. I signed up to do curls THATS IT!! 

Unfortunately that is the name of the game now. There’s no avoiding it!

Seriously though, lace wigs and lace frontals have had the game on lock now for almost a decade. I first started seeing lace frontals in 2013, after the girls grew bored with lace closures.
I for sure didn’t think it was going to stay around. I remember saying 

“this is toooo messy” 
“These don’t last long”
“Women are going to loose edges”

Y’all shut me right up. I had to learn the technique, because the industry was shifting whether I wanted to get on the wave or not. The stylist that got on the wave are now experts. Performing the service is second nature to them. Next came ponytail…with frontals. I was like, I was like “what is this hybrid shit”. Now the thing is tape-ins. Again the industry is shifting, and again a lot of stylist are being left behind. Surviving for now, stuck making the same amount of money, wondering whats next for their care, and what happened.

My friend, this industry will continue to change. New girls are bing released day and they seem to be inherently great at doing hair. Its time to decide what nexts for you. 

Are you IN OR OUT? 

If you're IN  lets set up a power hour to discuss what areas you need improvement and work on a strategy to win TOGETHER.
If you’re OUT lets set up a power hour to figure out an escape strategy.

Good Hair VS Bad Hair 💎💇🏾‍♀️

With so many people selling is hair so distinguish between what’s good and what’s great. 

Pay attention to verbiage for quality Virgin & Raw 

Virgin hair is mixed bundles with hair from multiple donors. There are different grades of Virgin hair. Good Virgin does have many or any colored strands (white, Grey, red). Multi colored hair in your bundles comes multi colored donor hair being colored or from synthetic filler fibers . 
Very hair is typically chemically treated so it has a “processed smell”. The texture is soft and shiny. It’s lightweight.  Vendors will tell you this hair can be colored to #27 or golden blonde. 

Raw hair is top of the line. It’s much more expensive. Each bundle comes from a single donor. Bundles are typically different shades and have a more course texture. These bundles are more dense. The hair moves different. They smell Iike….hair.  Vendors will say this hair can be colored to 613 or white blonde.

Signed a nigga who is weary. 

It’s crazy I’m a guy who is ready for his soft girl era 😂😂

Over the weekend I overheard a convo from a corporate professional in sabbatical explaining what exactly a sabbatical was. 

Bruhhh 🤯

I said to myself I need one of those. 
A 6 week paid pause to simply catch your breathe. I have been in grind mind for 13 consecutive years. I used to work on vacation. I never took the time to decide how I wanted to live or what I wanted to do. It was one play after next just trying to make it. 

I hit weary last super where I mentally checked out. I was burned out. I was over hit. I just needed to breathe. I needed to process. It took about 6 months to get myself back to a level 1 when I normally was a 10. That’s how depleted I was. Recognize when your depleted and not defeated. 

Pause for the cause lil baby.

Let’s be clear. 

If you’re talented learn to market your talents better. 
We all out here trying to get it and it a proven fact that the best marketer wins. 

No is obliged to support you, like you, or like your content. If you’re not getting the support/bookings/ sales/ engagement that you think you should be getting stop blaming the audience and look with in. 

Could by marketing be better? 
Could the quality of my content be better? 
Is my product or service something that people need? 
Are my guest enjoying their shopping experience with me? 

At this big age I don’t believe in popularity. Either you work for it or you don’t. This is small town thinking at its finest. Why are you worried about a small town when the world is your stage? 

Am I being mean??

Transparent Moment: 

I was a call with my bro @marc.coley (his prophetic business school & accountability group is 💣 bomb) listening to how this entrepreneur had everything then lost it and got it more because he listened to God on when to pivot.

Not gone lie he made a nigga cry. 
 Why? Because I’m in pivotal point in my life. Somewhere between I miss how things used to and I want something new & better. 

This quote was my reminder that God got me so far when I literally started my dream at 23 in my moms house why would he short  change me on next 23 years.  How could the next chapter not be great with all I gain from those past experiences. 

All I’m saying is your best days are still ahead, pivot, re invent yourself as many times as you need.
 
We all see how it’s working for Blac Chyna 😜
Help me understand how this works when you still have to put makeup up under the baby hair and then on the lace to blend!?

Yes it sucks for those that earned it but I hate that y’all turning this into borderline classism issue as though because you had it 1st it makes somewhat better.  That’s exactly why social media is problematic and somewhat weird TO ME. 

I’m not mad at @instagram for taking at advantage of the most popular & lucrative Business model out right now. It would have been foolish not to.

ANYWAYS Beauty Professionals IF you have grown a large audience that generates you income protect it! The direct customer service is enough for the business expense 😂
 
For the rest of y’all focus on unbigging that back….jk jk my back a lil big too ❤️

I’m not sure who this is for, but turn the page. Start a new chapter. Give yourself permission to pivot. Get uncomfortable for your peace.

Time management is important to me as an entrepreneur wearing many hats. I use a method called time blocking to help delegate my time for self care, exercise, deep work, personal task, and education. I began using this method years ago when I was a stylist and found myself overwhelmed with having so much to do and not enough time to do it. Remember it’s a marathon and you must pace yourself. 
I spent this week testing and tweaking different time allocations that work with my natural day to day flow. Now that this done my next step is to enter it into my calendar so that I’m unavailable during times of deep work, and to set alarms to let me know when one block is ending and another is beginning. 

I used 👉🏾https://www.calculator.net/calorie-calculator.html

Also I remove all social media from my phone most of the day and only sign in during my buffer blocks to stop me 🛑 from casually strolling. That’s a bad habit of mine that can eat up hours of my day. Hope this helps. #productivity #timeblocking

And they running out of patience 

In the words of Beyoncé “I took some time to live my life” and y’all still on here arguing about unprofessional stylist and how clients got you messed up. Let’s cut the crap! 

Ever since social media and I’ll even say the introduction of the lace wig the black sector of the industry has been a shit show. Now that our techniques are displayed for common content everybody and they lil sister is a “celebrity stylist” and it’s making it extremely hard for those who studied their craft. Being a stylist isn’t a trend or get rich quick scheme and I personally believe we should introduce some gate keeping.  The problem is because the clients see so much online for free that they believe the job is easy therefore they question our prices. Also, these kids see the same content and prices and think as long as they can lay a wig it’s up for them. 

Solution:
1. stylist stop showing all your techniques unless it’s marketing for a certification. Also have qualifications and etiquette training with your programs. 

2. Clients: stop going to people solely based on content. Ask if they are licensed, don’t go to anyone’s home unless you are referred, and stop thinking you can do it yourself because you watched some amateur on YouTube. 

That is all for my Ted Talk. Comment below 👇🏾 if I missed anything

Finding and keeping good assistants is a task!

What I’ve found is you can’t treat the job like their shadowing you. 

You have to consider all the steps it takes to do their job and break each one down into a system that is easy to duplicate. This cuts down on confusion which leads to them feeling confident about their job and staying with you longer. 

You have to go into thinking like an educator not a boss. Hope this helps anyone with or looking to hire an assistant.

At some point the clients slow down or you slow down it’s almost certain. Have you taken into consideration what’s next for you? 

I began plotting my escape in 2018 when I was 30. I began by cutting my expenses down to where it only cost me about $1000 to live per month. With all the Monday I saved I invested into @thebando_atl . I then began to push my wig sales. In 2020 when the pandemic hit I tripled my online sales. I retired from the chair to be the CEO & CMO of my wig company @eleven11extensions in 2021 . It’s been ups and downs and honestly if I could do it again I would have waited longer. Why you ask? I could have gotten way more money before my exit. Either way I’m happy with my decision. This is just my first retirement I’m still young enough to find a new passion to build all over again.
